|kun=つる-, たず-, つ-
|nanori=たず, ず, か, つ, づ
}}

{{der-top}}
* {{ja-r|鶴が音|たず が ね}}: a [[crane]]'s [[call]], the [[sound]] made by a crane
* {{ja-r|鶴群|たず むら}}: a [[flock]] or [[crane]]s
{{der-bottom}}

{{ja-kanjitab|つる|yomi=k}}
{{wikipedia|lang=ja|ツル}}
Given a crane's long neck and how the bird hunts, possibly related to {{m|ja|蔓|tr=tsuru||vine}}; {{m|ja|弦|tr=tsuru||bowstring; musical instrument string}}; {{ja-l|釣る}}, {{m|ja|吊る|tr=tsuru||to hang down; to string up; to fish}}. Given how cranes flock together, possibly related also to {{m|ja|連る|tr=tsuru}}, older root form of modern verb {{m|ja|連れる|tr=tsureru||to accompany}}. That said, {{ja-l|連る}} also appears to ultimately derive from {{m|ja|蔓|tr=tsuru||vine}}.

Vovin (2008) considers it possibly related to an ancestor of {{cog|ko|두루미|tr=durumi||crane}}, with a root-final ''-m'' vanishing later, leaving only a Kansai accent pattern behind.<ref>{{cite-book|title=Proto-Japanese: Issues and Prospects|editors=Bjarke Frellesvig and John Whitman|year=2008|chapter=7|section=Proto-Japanese beyond the accent system|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|location=Amsterdam; Philadelphia|pages=140-156|chapterurl=https://www.academia.edu/19253123/Proto-Japanese_beyond_the_accent_system}}</ref>

The reading ''tsuru'' is first seen used to mean {{m|en|crane|a crane|pos=the bird}} from the late [[w:Heian period|Heian period]]. Prior to that time, the only reading used for the bird was ''tazu''. However, the kanji {{lang|ja|鶴}} was used in the [[w:Man'yōshū|''Man'yōshū'']] as a phonetic [[ateji]] for the verb ending ''-tsuru'', suggesting that ''tsuru'' may have already existed as an everyday term meaning {{m|en|crane|a crane}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

{{der-top}}
* {{ja-r|鶴が城|^つる が ^じょう}}: the [[castle]] in [[w:Aizu Wakamatsu|Aizu Wakamatsu]], [[w:Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima Prefecture]]
* {{ja-r|鶴三|^つるぞう}}: a male given name
{{der-mid}}
* {{ja-r|姉羽鶴|あねはづる}}: a smaller species of [[crane]], ''[[Anthropoides virgo]]''
* {{ja-r|紅鶴|べにづる}}: [[flamingo]]
{{der-bottom}}
